[4] Japan (Miyazaki), suspected 2nd outbreak
Date: Tue, 23 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Kyodo via Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/T13097.htm>

A fresh outbreak of bird flu was suspected in
Japan on Tuesday [23 Jan 2007] after 250 birds
died at a poultry farm in southwestern Japan, Kyodo news agency reported.
Kyodo said the birds had died at a farm in
Miyazaki Prefecture, where earlier this month the
government confirmed a case of the lethal H5N1
strain of the virus -- Japan's first such case in 3 years.
Local officials were conducting tests to see
whether the deaths were from bird flu, Kyodo
added. Even if an initial test proves positive, confirmation could take days.
Neither agriculture ministry nor prefectural
officials could confirm the Kyodo report.
Renewed fears over the disease have rippled
across Asia recently. Hong Kong confirmed on
Monday that 3 more dead birds found in the city
carried the H5N1 virus, the third such case this month in the wealthy city.
Miyazaki on Japan's southernmost island of Kyushu
is the country's top breeder of chickens.
In 2004, Japan had 4 outbreaks of the H5N1 type
strain in poultry between January and March,
including an outbreak in Kyoto in western Japan
that led to the disposal of about 240 000 chickens and 20 million eggs.
--
